WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.932 --> 00:00:02.740
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: Well,
today I wanted to talk

00:00:02.740 --> 00:00:07.980
about exchanges and
clearinghouses, primarily

00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:09.230
stock exchanges.

00:00:11.860 --> 00:00:16.170
So, these are places,
where shares in

00:00:16.170 --> 00:00:19.060
corporations are traded.

00:00:19.060 --> 00:00:23.190
And I think, it's good to devote
a whole session to

00:00:23.190 --> 00:00:29.720
them, because exchange is
central to economics.

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:31.130
In fact, I was struck
recently.

00:00:31.130 --> 00:00:35.510
I was re-reading the
presidential

00:00:35.510 --> 00:00:40.030
address of my old teacher.

00:00:40.030 --> 00:00:44.310
When I was an undergraduate at
University of Michigan, I took

00:00:44.310 --> 00:00:47.334
a course by Professor
Kenneth Boulding.

00:00:52.430 --> 00:00:55.700
I suppose, I'm influenced
by him.

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:58.160
When he was elected president
of the American Economic

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:02.360
Association, he gave a
talk about economics.

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:05.880
And he had an interesting
definition of economics.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:07.570
What is economics?

00:01:07.570 --> 00:01:10.120
There's a lot of definitions
given for the field, but one

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:13.370
definition is the theory of the

00:01:13.370 --> 00:01:17.210
allocation of scarce resources.

00:01:17.210 --> 00:01:21.030
That's, by some definition,
what the essence

00:01:21.030 --> 00:01:22.410
of economics is.

00:01:22.410 --> 00:01:24.670
But Boulding said, that doesn't
sound right to him,

00:01:24.670 --> 00:01:30.000
because political science is
about the allocation of scarce

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.340
resources, and so is --

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:35.430
even the family is an

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:37.810
instrument of scarce resources.

00:01:37.810 --> 00:01:41.900
So, Boulding said in --

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:47.280
it was his 1969 presidential
address --

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:51.390
that economics is the
study of exchange.

00:01:56.050 --> 00:01:59.880
Obviously, it's prices and
quantities that economics

00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:05.500
emphasizes, and those are
parameters of an exchange.

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:11.760
So let's say, that
equals economics.

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:13.160
I'm reminded of another book.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.180
I'm talking in very general
terms first, and then I'm

00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:17.990
going to focus in on
stock exchanges.

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:21.940
But I'm reminded of another
really important book, which I

00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:33.930
read so many years ago, by Karl
Polanyi called The Great

00:02:33.930 --> 00:02:35.180
Transformation.

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:47.890
And that was written in 1944.

00:02:47.890 --> 00:02:49.400
What is the great
transformation?

00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:52.860
Well, for Polanyi, it's the
invention of exchange.

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:58.350
He said, what is the most
important invention of man?

00:02:58.350 --> 00:03:01.490
Maybe, it's exchange.

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:09.610
According to his history of
humankind, this was a

00:03:09.610 --> 00:03:13.280
relatively recent invention,
Neolithic or

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:15.020
more recent than that.

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:22.110
He argues that in primitive
societies, there is really no

00:03:22.110 --> 00:03:24.980
arm's length exchange.

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:30.160
An arm's length exchange is one,
where you just quote a

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:34.180
price and a quantity, and you
don't have any other business.

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:36.340
The price and the quantity
sum it up.

00:03:36.340 --> 00:03:38.630
It's a business transaction.

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:43.400
But Polanyi argued, that until
just something on the order of

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:47.150
10,000 years ago, there were
no business transactions.

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:52.150
There was only gift exchange.

00:03:52.150 --> 00:03:54.730
There were relationships
people had.

00:03:54.730 --> 00:03:57.610
And you would solidify a
relationship by making a gift

00:03:57.610 --> 00:04:01.089
to someone else, and then
that person would later

00:04:01.089 --> 00:04:06.060
reciprocate, but there's no
price, there's no exchange.

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:08.250
So, he claims that the
development of our

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:12.280
civilization is really the
result of the development of

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:15.950
the idea of exchange, and then,
an amplification of the

00:04:15.950 --> 00:04:19.980
idea as it became more
and more pervasive.

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:21.760
By the way, I've since
learned --

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:23.830
I thought Polanyi was
very impressive --

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:28.000
but some anthropologists
question, whether there wasn't

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.510
exchange more than
10,000 years ago.

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:33.290
And they cite evidence.

00:04:33.290 --> 00:04:37.790
One kind of evidence that's
found of this is, that certain

00:04:37.790 --> 00:04:43.330
commodities, even in the
Paleolithic times, certain

00:04:43.330 --> 00:04:47.530
commodities are found far from
where they were mined.

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:51.410
Like flint to make stone
tools, or ochre

00:04:51.410 --> 00:04:54.010
to make body paint.

00:04:54.010 --> 00:04:56.875
And they figured out where --
you can do a chemical analysis

00:04:56.875 --> 00:04:59.910
and you can figure out
where it was mined.

00:04:59.910 --> 00:05:04.240
And then, if you find that it
arrived somewhere 1,000 miles

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.740
away, there must have been
exchange, right?

00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:08.590
The cave --

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:09.444
no?

00:05:09.444 --> 00:05:11.764
STUDENT: Couldn't they have
just killed someone?

00:05:11.764 --> 00:05:12.640
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: OK.

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:16.390
It could have been, that they
just killed someone, right.

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:18.000
So, I guess nobody knows.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:25.020
But anyway, some anthropologists
argue that

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:26.500
there was exchange.

00:05:26.500 --> 00:05:28.340
Maybe, it was too pervasive.

00:05:28.340 --> 00:05:30.720
Of course, people did kill a lot
of people in those days,

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:32.970
too, anthropologists report.

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:36.300
So, maybe Polanyi had
it exactly right.

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:38.940
But I think, he had it at least
approximately right,

00:05:38.940 --> 00:05:42.470
that exchange has become a
bigger and bigger part of our

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:45.860
lives, and that's modern
civilization.

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:56.670
I'm going to talk mostly about
financial exchange.

00:05:56.670 --> 00:05:59.570
That's the subject
of this course.

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:01.670
But I can be a little
bit more general.

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:04.420
I wanted to start by
distinguishing a

00:06:04.420 --> 00:06:07.500
broker and a dealer.

00:06:12.230 --> 00:06:14.225
What's the difference?

00:06:14.225 --> 00:06:16.510
It's a fundamental thing.

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:17.760
A broker --

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:22.880
actually, I've got this
almost as a slogan --

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:31.470
a broker acts on behalf of
others as an agent to earn a

00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:32.650
commission.

00:06:32.650 --> 00:06:40.970
So, it's for others, trades for
others as an agent for a

00:06:40.970 --> 00:06:41.776
commission.

00:06:41.776 --> 00:06:43.155
A commission is a fee.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.200
What is a dealer?

00:06:51.200 --> 00:07:00.980
A dealer trades for himself
or herself, acting as a

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:09.700
principal, not an agent, and
profits from a markup.

00:07:14.720 --> 00:07:18.910
So, I can give you an
example of each.

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:23.060
When you buy or sell a house,
do you get a real estate

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:26.910
broker or a real
estate dealer?

00:07:26.910 --> 00:07:28.140
That's almost obvious, right?

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:31.440
Because you heard the
term real estate

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:33.310
broker so many times.

00:07:33.310 --> 00:07:37.160
When you buy or sell a house,
you commission a broker, and

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:42.110
you agree on a contract that
pays the real estate broker a

00:07:42.110 --> 00:07:44.700
certain sum of money --
maybe 6% of the value

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:46.350
of the house --

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:50.470
if a buyer is found.

00:07:50.470 --> 00:07:54.400
And then, the broker doesn't
buy your house, right?

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:56.550
So, the broker is an agent.

00:07:56.550 --> 00:08:01.790
And the 6% is the commission
that the broker gets, if he or

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:10.240
she is successful in finding
the other side of the deal.

00:08:10.240 --> 00:08:12.500
What's an example of a dealer?

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:15.280
An antique dealer.

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:19.460
Suppose, you're buying a chest
of drawers for your apartment.

00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:23.220
You go to an antique store, and
there's someone there --

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:24.470
your antique dealer --

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:37.000
who has furniture, that he now
owns, having bought it, and

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.790
makes a profit by selling it
to you at a higher price,

00:08:40.790 --> 00:08:42.300
namely with a markup.

00:08:42.300 --> 00:08:47.050
He marks up the price that
he paid for the item.

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:51.550
But let me just ask you,
why is it that way?

00:08:51.550 --> 00:08:54.750
Why are antiques sold
by dealers and

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:56.000
real estate by brokers?

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:02.000
I recently had a discussion with
Guillermo Ordonez, who is

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.470
an assistant professor here, and
we were wondering, maybe

00:09:05.470 --> 00:09:07.110
there are real estate dealers.

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:14.940
Oliver helped us and found,
actually, in Germany, a couple

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:18.230
of real estate dealers.

00:09:18.230 --> 00:09:23.330
But only like a couple, and we
couldn't find any in the U.S.

00:09:23.330 --> 00:09:26.445
And we had searched around in
many other countries, and

00:09:26.445 --> 00:09:30.590
there was just virtually none,
no real estate dealers.

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:33.990
Anyone have any idea why?

00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:35.300
I'm asking you to think.

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:36.830
It's a little --

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:39.740
or does anyone come from a
country, where they have real

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:40.540
estate dealers?

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:42.700
And that would end
it, if you --

00:09:42.700 --> 00:09:44.230
I bet not, right?

00:09:44.230 --> 00:09:46.930
Well, what about antique
brokers?

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:47.670
Why not that?

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:49.170
Have you ever heard of
an antique broker?

00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:54.500
Maybe, there are.

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:56.290
But it's an interesting
question.

00:09:56.290 --> 00:09:59.430
It seems like some markets are
naturally dealer markets, and

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:01.660
some are broker markets.

00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:06.480
We thought of one explanation,
why there aren't real estate

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:09.940
dealers, at least in
the United States.

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:15.490
We learned that a dealer has
to pay income tax on the

00:10:15.490 --> 00:10:20.150
profits from a deal, and that
is at a higher rate than a

00:10:20.150 --> 00:10:25.400
capital gains tax, and so
that closes people out.

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:28.070
You wouldn't want to be a real
estate dealer, because you'd

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:32.820
end up paying a higher tax.

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:36.710
The other thing is, I wonder
if there's something about

00:10:36.710 --> 00:10:42.530
information, that someone who
deals in real estate --

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:46.180
it's just too hard to know
what to pay for a house.

00:10:46.180 --> 00:10:48.260
It's just so subjective.

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:50.540
You can make big mistakes, if
you're going to buy houses,

00:10:50.540 --> 00:10:54.100
and then resell them at a
markup, because the market is

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:59.140
just so variable, and it
ultimately changes quickly.

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:00.860
Maybe it's too risky.

00:11:00.860 --> 00:11:01.490
I don't know.

00:11:01.490 --> 00:11:02.650
I'm trying to think.

00:11:02.650 --> 00:11:04.440
But of course, there are
real estate dealers,

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:05.690
it's just very rare.

00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:10.640
So, we're going to talk
about stock markets.

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:12.930
Which do you think stock
markets are?

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:17.640
Are they dealer markets
or broker markets?

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:21.050
Well, the answer is both.

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:25.130
And now it's not as clear, and
I'll come back to this.

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:38.030
The New York Stock Exchange, New
York Stock Exchange in New

00:11:38.030 --> 00:11:42.570
York is a broker market.

00:11:42.570 --> 00:11:45.911
Or they would say, an
auction market.

00:11:45.911 --> 00:11:49.880
It's a continuous double auction
market, where a broker

00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:53.320
facilitates the trades.

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:59.840
The NASDAQ market is
a dealer market.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:07.180
So, you pay commissions to your
broker at the New York

00:12:07.180 --> 00:12:09.500
Stock Exchange, you pay
a markup to your

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:10.720
dealer at the NASDAQ.

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:24.170
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:12:24.170 --> 00:12:26.130
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: I
thought I will start by

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:32.490
talking about stock exchanges,
and historically --

00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:37.680
And I have a lot to say.

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:38.910
I can't cover it all --

00:12:38.910 --> 00:12:40.890
I was going to start with
ancient Rome --

00:12:40.890 --> 00:12:42.870
I think I mentioned
that before.

00:12:42.870 --> 00:12:46.020
But the --

00:12:46.020 --> 00:12:47.380
I'm getting there
in my notes --

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:52.420
the ancient Roman stock exchange
is the first stock

00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:56.250
exchange, that, I think,
anyone knows about.

00:12:56.250 --> 00:12:59.820
But traders --

00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:10.710
I'm relying on the research of
Ulrike Malmendier, who has

00:13:10.710 --> 00:13:13.270
studied the ancient Roman
stock exchanges

00:13:13.270 --> 00:13:16.380
much as can be studied.

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:18.030
There's not that much
evidence about it.

00:13:18.030 --> 00:13:25.610
But the traders met outdoors
on the Roman Forum at the

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:28.050
Temple of Castor.

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:35.000
That's where you went to
buy and sell shares.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.595
The shares in Latin were
called partes --

00:13:37.595 --> 00:13:40.050
I don't know if I covered
this or not --

00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:41.300
and the companies were
called publicani.

00:13:47.030 --> 00:13:51.550
The peculiar nature of the
ancient Roman corporations is

00:13:51.550 --> 00:13:55.050
that they sold -- their
customers were the government.

00:13:55.050 --> 00:13:58.650
And so, they did services for
the government, like provide

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:02.250
horses for the army, or they
would feed the geese on the

00:14:02.250 --> 00:14:04.560
Roman forum, on the
Roman capital.

00:14:04.560 --> 00:14:07.210
They always fed the geese there,
because the geese were

00:14:07.210 --> 00:14:11.940
hallowed in Ancient Rome,
because they once warned of an

00:14:11.940 --> 00:14:14.170
invasion by cackling.

00:14:14.170 --> 00:14:17.760
So, there was a publicanus
that was in charge

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:19.010
of feeding the geese.

00:14:23.310 --> 00:14:26.395
And also, they would talk
about share prices.

00:14:26.395 --> 00:14:29.350
It's known, that they would go
up and down, even then, but

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:32.710
there's no data on their
share prices.

00:14:32.710 --> 00:14:37.340
It seemed, that there was a long
gap for stock exchanges

00:14:37.340 --> 00:14:41.920
after the fall of the Roman
Empire, and the publicani

00:14:41.920 --> 00:14:43.750
disappeared.

00:14:43.750 --> 00:14:49.800
And there was a wide variety
of financial arrangements,

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:52.350
some of them resembling
corporations.

00:14:52.350 --> 00:14:58.320
But the advent of the rebirth
of the stock exchange didn't

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:05.080
occur until 1602 in Amsterdam,
when the --

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:06.360
I mentioned this before --

00:15:06.360 --> 00:15:11.600
when the Dutch East India
Company started trading.

00:15:11.600 --> 00:15:18.970
And then, Jonathan's
Coffee House --

00:15:22.127 --> 00:15:23.630
I like that story --

00:15:26.540 --> 00:15:29.510
in London.

00:15:29.510 --> 00:15:31.930
Lots of people would get
together and talk there, and

00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:38.675
coffee houses became a big
thing in the late 1600s.

00:15:38.675 --> 00:15:43.250
And somebody started posting
stock prices on the wall at

00:15:43.250 --> 00:15:46.790
Jonathan's Coffee House by --

00:15:46.790 --> 00:15:48.140
what was the date --

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:50.470
1698.

00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:53.220
And so, the London Stock
Exchange grew out of

00:15:53.220 --> 00:15:55.420
Jonathan's Coffee House.

00:15:55.420 --> 00:15:59.090
And then, moving forward in
time, now we're going to get

00:15:59.090 --> 00:16:00.610
lots of countries, but
I'll mention the

00:16:00.610 --> 00:16:01.860
New York Stock Exchange.

00:16:04.370 --> 00:16:14.790
The traders of shares in the
United States met outside, in

00:16:14.790 --> 00:16:20.090
1792, under a buttonwood tree.

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:21.470
I'll put buttonwood.

00:16:21.470 --> 00:16:22.630
That's a curious name.

00:16:22.630 --> 00:16:28.000
I think that's just
a common tree that

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.570
we still have around.

00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:32.380
And they signed the agreement
to form the

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:33.630
New York Stock Exchange.

00:16:41.070 --> 00:16:42.130
What else?

00:16:42.130 --> 00:16:43.900
Next, in my little history.

00:16:43.900 --> 00:16:46.609
India.

00:16:46.609 --> 00:16:52.510
By the 1850s, there
were in Mumbai --

00:16:52.510 --> 00:16:55.800
or then called Bombay --

00:16:55.800 --> 00:17:00.990
there were traders under
a famous banyan tree.

00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:03.880
They were all outdoors.

00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:06.599
In Bombay.

00:17:06.599 --> 00:17:08.270
Banyan trees are
more impressive

00:17:08.270 --> 00:17:10.450
than buttonwood trees.

00:17:10.450 --> 00:17:20.510
But it was by 1875, the Bombay
Stock Exchange was founded.

00:17:20.510 --> 00:17:21.760
So, that's the BFC.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:27.400
So, that's been around
for over 100 years.

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:29.760
But things have happened
more recently.

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:32.340
One thing that's been shaking
things up -- these are very

00:17:32.340 --> 00:17:34.750
venerable old institutions --

00:17:34.750 --> 00:17:38.060
what's been shaking things
up is the advent

00:17:38.060 --> 00:17:41.400
of electronic trading.

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:45.830
And these were kind of
old-fashioned, venerable

00:17:45.830 --> 00:17:46.480
institutions.

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:48.710
Do you know what happens at the
New York Stock Exchange,

00:17:48.710 --> 00:17:51.470
what happened then and
still happens today?

00:17:51.470 --> 00:17:55.100
There's a floor called the
trading floor, and the various

00:17:55.100 --> 00:17:59.460
brokers meet there, just like
in Jonathan's Coffee House.

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:01.730
They actually physically come
to the floor and they stand

00:18:01.730 --> 00:18:07.440
around, and there are posts
for each stock.

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:10.080
And if today you think, you have
a customer who wants to

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:14.740
buy IBM stock, then you go over
to the IBM crowd, and

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:17.680
there's a crowd of brokers
there who are trading.

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:20.820
And you just do it, verbally.

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:25.170
You talk to them and
you make a trade.

00:18:25.170 --> 00:18:26.880
That's really old-fashioned.

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:28.910
There is something more
electronic and more modern

00:18:28.910 --> 00:18:32.340
about the New York Stock
Exchange, but that specialist

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:35.570
post behavior still persists.

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:38.950
Most of the world is switching
over to electronic trading,

00:18:38.950 --> 00:18:41.170
and so things happen that --

00:18:41.170 --> 00:18:44.890
so, for example, in India they
developed another stock

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:48.850
exchange called the National
Stock Exchange,

00:18:48.850 --> 00:18:54.430
and that was in 1992.

00:18:54.430 --> 00:18:58.720
And the National Stock Exchange
was all-electronic,

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:00.385
and so it was the
modern version.

00:19:00.385 --> 00:19:03.650
It's rapidly gaining on the
Bombay Stock Exchange.

00:19:07.090 --> 00:19:11.190
So, let me go a little
bit more forward.

00:19:11.190 --> 00:19:14.840
China, because of the communist
government, did not

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:19.810
have a stock exchange
until 1990.

00:19:19.810 --> 00:19:22.150
And there were two stock
exchanges founded in

00:19:22.150 --> 00:19:24.710
China in 1990 --

00:19:24.710 --> 00:19:29.570
Shanghai, Shenzhen.

00:19:33.180 --> 00:19:35.850
And at least the Shanghai Stock
Exchange is owned by the

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:39.496
Chinese government, and that's
why Laura Cha, when she talked

00:19:39.496 --> 00:19:41.090
to us about that --

00:19:41.090 --> 00:19:44.000
she was on the China Securities
Regulatory

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:45.960
Commission, which actually
owned the

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:47.210
Shanghai Stock Exchange.

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:58.250
Oh, Latin America.

00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:05.350
Sao Paolo Stock Exchange,
1890.

00:20:05.350 --> 00:20:07.940
Mexico has only one stock
exchange, but it

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:11.550
was founded in 1894.

00:20:11.550 --> 00:20:14.180
So, we seem to have like two
different kinds of exchanges.

00:20:14.180 --> 00:20:17.210
We have the old exchanges, which
are at least 100 years

00:20:17.210 --> 00:20:20.620
old, and we have the new
electronic exchanges.

00:20:20.620 --> 00:20:23.200
Things have really sped
up with the advent

00:20:23.200 --> 00:20:26.110
of electronic exchanges.

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:30.250
So, I mentioned the New York
Stock Exchange, which started

00:20:30.250 --> 00:20:36.380
on the street outdoors and is an
old-fashioned exchange that

00:20:36.380 --> 00:20:38.850
has been slow to update.

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:42.810
But more recently, we have --

00:20:42.810 --> 00:20:44.660
I mentioned it already --

00:20:44.660 --> 00:20:45.910
NASDAQ.

00:20:52.420 --> 00:20:55.670
It stands for, originally,
National Association of

00:20:55.670 --> 00:21:01.530
Securities Dealers Automatic
Quotation System, which was

00:21:01.530 --> 00:21:05.876
created in the 1970s.

00:21:05.876 --> 00:21:09.840
It's an interesting story
about NASDAQ.

00:21:09.840 --> 00:21:13.390
In the '70s, the New York Stock
Exchange with highly

00:21:13.390 --> 00:21:14.160
prestigious.

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:18.990
It was the big board,
the place.

00:21:18.990 --> 00:21:23.340
And a critical element of as
stock exchange is, that, in

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:26.360
order to get your stocks traded
on the exchange, you

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:29.590
have to satisfy listing
requirements.

00:21:29.590 --> 00:21:32.260
So, the New York Stock Exchange
would examine any

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:36.440
corporation that wanted to be
listed on the exchange, and it

00:21:36.440 --> 00:21:39.260
was the prestigious,
big exchange,

00:21:39.260 --> 00:21:41.400
so it had high standards.

00:21:41.400 --> 00:21:45.420
So, the company had to have a
history of earnings, it had to

00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:48.560
have the right kind
of management

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:50.430
structure and board.

00:21:50.430 --> 00:21:54.940
A lot of things were checked out
by the exchange, and as a

00:21:54.940 --> 00:22:00.190
result, the way it would work
in the 1970s, a startup

00:22:00.190 --> 00:22:02.190
company could never
get traded on the

00:22:02.190 --> 00:22:03.880
New York Stock Exchange.

00:22:03.880 --> 00:22:08.790
It would be traded, instead,
by brokers off-exchange, or

00:22:08.790 --> 00:22:14.380
''over-the-counter.'' So, OTC
means ''over-the-counter,"

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:18.570
that means not on an exchange.

00:22:18.570 --> 00:22:27.580
So, in the 1970s and earlier,
the over-the-counter brokers

00:22:27.580 --> 00:22:30.670
would deal with each other,
informally with telephone

00:22:30.670 --> 00:22:32.800
calls, or actually out
on the street.

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:35.490
Meet each other out on the
sidewalk originally, and then

00:22:35.490 --> 00:22:36.740
they got telephones.

00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:41.645
And they had some record,
which they called ''pink

00:22:41.645 --> 00:22:45.440
sheets,'' because they
were traditionally

00:22:45.440 --> 00:22:47.110
printed on pink paper.

00:22:47.110 --> 00:22:52.690
These were lists of dealers' buy
and sell quotes on prices

00:22:52.690 --> 00:22:55.622
of over-the-counter stocks.

00:22:55.622 --> 00:22:59.110
The National Association of
Securities Dealers, then, was

00:22:59.110 --> 00:23:02.600
an organization of these
over-the-counter traders.

00:23:02.600 --> 00:23:07.410
And in the early '70s,
they set up the first

00:23:07.410 --> 00:23:10.650
computerized system.

00:23:10.650 --> 00:23:13.640
They decided that everyone's
telephoning everybody --

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:25.030
let's create a system that
really works and that gets us

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:26.280
the information.

00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:33.960
And so, that was the NASDAQ
system, the first computer

00:23:33.960 --> 00:23:38.230
based system, which has now
increasingly taken over much

00:23:38.230 --> 00:23:39.330
of the world.

00:23:39.330 --> 00:23:42.060
I shouldn't imply that the New
York Stock Exchange was

00:23:42.060 --> 00:23:44.760
entirely a laggard on this.

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:48.800
Electronics played a role in
stocks going back very early.

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:53.330
The New York Stock Exchange
used telegraph in the 19th

00:23:53.330 --> 00:23:55.690
century to convey
prices, and they

00:23:55.690 --> 00:23:57.980
invented ticker tape machines.

00:23:57.980 --> 00:24:01.460
A ticker tape machine is an
electronic printer that would

00:24:01.460 --> 00:24:05.090
print out stock prices.

00:24:05.090 --> 00:24:07.630
And in fact, Thomas Edison,
the inventor, his first

00:24:07.630 --> 00:24:10.960
invention was actually a
ticker tape machine.

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:12.630
That was in, I think,
the 1870s.

00:24:12.630 --> 00:24:14.890
It printed stock prices.

00:24:14.890 --> 00:24:18.490
But all it was, was a record of
what had traded recently.

00:24:18.490 --> 00:24:23.630
It wasn't a system that
helped you trade.

00:24:23.630 --> 00:24:27.170
You just reported what had
happened, it was historical.

00:24:27.170 --> 00:24:32.210
So, I wanted to show you, what
NASDAQ created in the '70s,

00:24:32.210 --> 00:24:38.600
and it's an order book, that
would be visible to everyone

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:39.850
who trades on it.

00:24:46.030 --> 00:24:52.060
Prior to discussing that,
I want to tell you about

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:56.990
different kinds of orders.

00:24:56.990 --> 00:25:01.520
If you buy and sell stock, and
you call up a broker and you

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:06.020
say, I want to buy and sell, the
simplest kind of order is

00:25:06.020 --> 00:25:14.380
a ''market order.'' And you
would specify the quantity.

00:25:14.380 --> 00:25:16.130
You would say, I
want to buy --

00:25:16.130 --> 00:25:17.400
and the name of the company,
of course --

00:25:17.400 --> 00:25:21.010
I want to buy 100 shares of
General Motors, or I want to

00:25:21.010 --> 00:25:22.720
sell 100 shares.

00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:24.010
But you don't name a price.

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:28.525
You'll find out, whatever
the price was.

00:25:28.525 --> 00:25:33.320
The broker will get you
the best price --

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:35.980
if he or she is a good broker,
will try to get you the best

00:25:35.980 --> 00:25:41.330
price, but it'll still be
unknown to you, because you

00:25:41.330 --> 00:25:42.920
didn't specify it.

00:25:42.920 --> 00:25:45.000
You might be unhappy
with the price.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:46.100
The price might be too
high [addition: if

00:25:46.100 --> 00:25:47.350
you want to buy shares].

00:25:47.350 --> 00:25:49.840
And then, the broker will say
to you, well, if you're

00:25:49.840 --> 00:25:52.320
unhappy, you should've
told me.

00:25:52.320 --> 00:25:55.810
You could have told me not to
pay more than a certain amount

00:25:55.810 --> 00:25:58.080
for a buy, or not to take
less than a certain

00:25:58.080 --> 00:26:00.040
amount for a sell.

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:07.370
So, the alternative is a ''limit
order.'' And so, with

00:26:07.370 --> 00:26:11.780
a limit order you give both
quantity and price.

00:26:14.330 --> 00:26:19.430
So, if it's a buy, I want to buy
so many shares but I don't

00:26:19.430 --> 00:26:22.400
want to pay more than such
and such a price.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:26.660
Then, the broker will keep
that on his or her

00:26:26.660 --> 00:26:29.340
books, until --

00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:33.060
well, whatever the agreement
between you and broker is.

00:26:33.060 --> 00:26:36.490
It might expire after the day
is over, or you could ask to

00:26:36.490 --> 00:26:38.970
have it kept on the book.

00:26:38.970 --> 00:26:45.640
And when the price becomes
available, which is no higher

00:26:45.640 --> 00:26:47.820
than your specified
price, then the

00:26:47.820 --> 00:26:49.390
order will be executed.

00:26:49.390 --> 00:26:51.810
Otherwise, it won't
be executed.

00:26:51.810 --> 00:26:55.120
And then, for a sell order, it
would be the same thing.

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:57.980
You specify both the quantity
and a price, and the order

00:26:57.980 --> 00:26:59.580
will be filled or
partly filled.

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:02.700
They might not be able to get
all of your quantity, but

00:27:02.700 --> 00:27:06.580
they'll fill as much as
they can of it at

00:27:06.580 --> 00:27:07.830
that price or lower.

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:14.600
And there's another kind of
order, called a ''stop

00:27:14.600 --> 00:27:24.420
order.'' With a stop order, you
also specify quantity and

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:28.240
price, but it's different.

00:27:28.240 --> 00:27:36.480
With a limit order, say it's a
buy limit order -- well, let's

00:27:36.480 --> 00:27:37.800
talk about sell.

00:27:37.800 --> 00:27:41.810
If it's a sell limit order, you
would sell the quantity at

00:27:41.810 --> 00:27:45.270
such and such a price
or higher.

00:27:45.270 --> 00:27:49.600
With a stop order, you would
sell that quantity at such and

00:27:49.600 --> 00:27:51.090
such a price or lower.

00:27:51.090 --> 00:27:52.470
Let's make that clear.

00:27:52.470 --> 00:27:56.570
A stop order, also called a
''stop loss order,'' is an

00:27:56.570 --> 00:28:02.240
order that you can place with a
broker to indicate, that I'm

00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:05.240
worried that this stock
might really collapse.

00:28:05.240 --> 00:28:08.660
I'm holding it, but I want you
to sell it, if the price

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:10.440
starts falling a lot.

00:28:10.440 --> 00:28:13.720
So, suppose the price
is $100 today --

00:28:13.720 --> 00:28:17.480
I could put in a stop loss order
at $80, and then, at

00:28:17.480 --> 00:28:20.720
least I know I can't lose more
than 20% of my investment,

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.090
because the broker will
immediately sell it, when the

00:28:23.090 --> 00:28:27.940
price of that stock
falls below $80.

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:31.830
There's also a buy stop order,
and that would be something

00:28:31.830 --> 00:28:34.350
that someone would rationally
do, if that person

00:28:34.350 --> 00:28:36.110
had shorted a stock.

00:28:36.110 --> 00:28:39.380
So, if you had shorted a stock,
and you were worried

00:28:39.380 --> 00:28:42.770
that the price would go up and
ruin you, you can leave with

00:28:42.770 --> 00:28:47.160
your broker a buy stop
order to sell it --

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:49.700
I mean, to buy the stock,
whenever the price exceeds a

00:28:49.700 --> 00:28:50.590
certain amount.

00:28:50.590 --> 00:28:52.900
And you would do that to prevent
yourself from having

00:28:52.900 --> 00:28:56.670
unlimited losses on your
short position.

00:28:56.670 --> 00:28:58.510
There's other kinds of orders,
but those are the

00:28:58.510 --> 00:28:59.910
main kinds of orders.

00:29:03.610 --> 00:29:06.220
Now, I wanted talk specifically
about limit

00:29:06.220 --> 00:29:08.750
orders -- that's the most
important kind.

00:29:08.750 --> 00:29:12.310
A lot of advisors say, never
place a market order.

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:14.430
Why should you ever
do a market order?

00:29:14.430 --> 00:29:17.180
There's always some price that
you'd be unhappy with.

00:29:17.180 --> 00:29:20.140
You might as well say that.

00:29:20.140 --> 00:29:23.100
And so, some exchanges don't
even allow market orders.

00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:29.420
So, let's talk about
limit orders.

00:29:29.420 --> 00:29:36.640
And what I wanted to show you
was, what a NASDAQ level II

00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:37.890
customer sees.

00:29:40.250 --> 00:29:43.310
NASDAQ is an organization --

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:47.360
now it's a firm traded on its
own stock exchange, it's

00:29:47.360 --> 00:29:49.620
called NASDAQ OMX --

00:29:49.620 --> 00:29:52.330
but if you want to subscribe
to NASDAQ, it's very

00:29:52.330 --> 00:29:54.220
expensive, I understand.

00:29:54.220 --> 00:30:00.100
So, you can subscribe at
level I or level II,

00:30:00.100 --> 00:30:02.320
which is more expensive.

00:30:02.320 --> 00:30:05.180
I was going to show you an
example of what you would see

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:08.860
on your computer screen, if you
subscribe to NASDAQ level

00:30:08.860 --> 00:30:12.580
II, for a particular stock.

00:30:12.580 --> 00:30:15.330
So, this is a hypothetical
limit

00:30:15.330 --> 00:30:18.530
order book for Microsoft.

00:30:22.910 --> 00:30:24.160
What it shows --

00:30:28.890 --> 00:30:31.960
